<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-080-284  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 080 284.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  Jan 15 1990 v218 n3 p26(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fiber must get tough to make it in the local loop. (telephonesystems) (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Eccleston, Douglas, J.; Sicotte, John R.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Fiber optic cable, now frequently found in long-haul,interexchange and interoffice telephone installations, is movinginto the local loop and feeder portions of telecommunicationsnetworks.andP;  Such installations expose fiber optic cable to morehandling and splicing, increasing the demands on the mechanicalperformance of the fiber.andP;  Although fiber is typically strongerthan the steel alloy and copper it replaces, its increasedexposure leads to concern about its tolerance for fatigue andabrasion.andP;  Corning Inc has developed a new fiber, called Titan,which is designed to perform better under the conditions found inlocal loop installations.andP;  Optical performance factors such asdispersion remain important, but mechanical performance willcontinue to increase in importance.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Corning Inc. (products).andO;Topic:     TelecommunicationsFiber opticsPerformance ImprovementTelephone systemsBell Regional Holding CompaniesTelephone companiesCablesCommunications CircuitsTelecommunication systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Glass resistance to abrasion. (graph)Coating abrasion test. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>